.TH LVRENAME 8 "LVM TOOLS 2.02.106(2) (2014-04-10)" "Sistina Software UK" \" -*- nroff -*-
.SH NAME
lvrename \- rename a logical volume
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B lvrename
.RB [ \-A | \-\-autobackup
.RI { y | n }]
.RB [ \-d | \-\-debug ]
.RB [ \-h | \-\-help ]
.RB [ \-t | \-\-test ]
.RB [ \-v | \-\-verbose ]
.RB [ \-\-version ]
.RB [ \-f | \-\-force ]
.RB [ \-\-noudevsync ]
.RI { OldLogicalVolume { Name | Path }
.IR NewLogicalVolume { Name | Path }
|
.I VolumeGroupName OldLogicalVolumeName NewLogicalVolumeName\fR}
.SH DESCRIPTION
lvrename renames a existin logical volume from
.IR OldLogicalVolume { Name | Path }
to
.IR NewLogicalVolume { Name | Path }.
.SH OPTIONS
See \fBlvm\fP(8) fo' common options.
.TP
.BR \-\-noudevsync
Disable udev synchronisation. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch. The
process aint gonna wait fo' notification from udev.
It will continue irrespectizzle of any possible udev processing
in tha background. Y'all KNOW dat shit, muthafucka!  Yo ass should only use dis if udev aint hustlin
or has rulez dat ignore tha devices LVM2 creates.
.SH EXAMPLE
To rename lvold up in volume crew vg02 ta lvnew:
.sp
.B lvrename /dev/vg02/lvold vg02/lvnew
.sp
An alternate syntax ta rename dis logical volume is:
.sp
.B lvrename vg02 lvold lvnew
.sp
